Completion:
This month some important Walmart news did not get the attention it deserved. The news wasn't some flashy announcement about a shiny new app or social media acquisition, and it didn’t involve any fancy press conference by executive leadership with its latest grand plans to change everything – again (again).
It was just one weekend in April when the world’s largest retailer quietly introduced a major upgrade at 40 pilot stores nationwide: the launch of the first phase of a mobile-enabled price check solution from Retale Corporation, called Price Check In Store. With the simple scan of a bar code on their phones using the free, dedicated Apple iOS application, customers can now see accurate prices for competing products nearby — including online offers such as Amazon Prime discounts—in store where they shop, and compare them with what is available elsewhere. What this means, quite simply put, is that Walmart has unlocked the power of the crowd…and may be starting the most significant initiative since eCommerce began more than two decades ago.

NEW YORK (AP) — Could the U.S. lose its top credit rating even if a deal is reached to raise America's borrowing limit?
It would be unprecedented but hardly impossible, especially given how much has changed since Standard & Poor’s stripped the nation of that distinction two years ago as it was being threatened with default because lawmakers couldn’t agree on what fiscal measures should accompany an increase in the debt ceiling. This time around Washington faces not just one deadline but three: the end of this month to prevent a government shutdown; early October when the Treasury Department exhausts the means to keep paying off bills without congressional permission and November 15 for the country’s ability to continue meeting other obligations like making Social Security payments.. That could cause yet another downgrade unless S&P sees evidence Congress can actually overcome political dysfunction to address these issues once they get kicked into gear.

MOSCOW (Reuters) - The FSB security agency said on Friday it was investigating a cyber attack against telecoms group Rostelecom by hackers claiming to have ties with U.S.-based intelligence services.
The agency said the Russian-speaking hacker group “Equation Group” had stolen passwords and other confidential information from the company’s servers over an unspecified period of time but that nothing important or dangerous for national security had been taken.
Rostelecom is state-owned, though many private firms operate as part of its infrastructure. It told Reuters on Monday it had carried out technical work after discovering unauthorized access but did not comment further when asked if customer data may have leaked.

Completion:
The NHS is still running Windows XP en masse, two and a half years after Microsoft stopped delivering bug fixes.
According to research from the University of Hull's Centre for Cybersecurity Information Assurance (CCSIA) there are 153 active computers at the Nuffield Orthopaedic Center in Oxford that remain on the operating system almost three years beyond its end-of-life date – with another six being planned or already installed. It was reported that one such machine contained details about an individual's "orthodontic treatment". All of the machines have been identified using CCSIA's vulnerability scanning service which costs £20 per device, but the center says it hasn’t received any offers to fix these systems since the discovery was made last week. In all cases the machines were not part of the hospital's main IT infrastructure but instead belonged to consultants who accessed their records via secure connections.
